To clarify the relationship between the two paradigms you described, let's create a TikZ diagram that visually represents the similarities and differences between the teacher-student model for a \( p \)-body Hopfield network and the Krotov method for training a dense neural network.

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
  block/.style={rectangle, draw=black, text width=4em, text centered, minimum height=3em},
  line/.style={draw, thick, ->, >=stealth'},
  cloud/.style={cloud, draw=black, aspect=2},
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

\node [block] (teacher) {Teacher};
\node [block, below=of teacher] (student) {Student};

\node [block, right=of teacher] (data) {Data};
\node [block, right=of student] (examples) {Examples};

\node [block, above=of data] (labels) {Labels};
\node [block, above=of examples] (patterns) {Patterns};

\path [line] (teacher) -- node[anchor=east] {Generates} (examples);
\path [line] (teacher) -- node[anchor=south] {Matches} (patterns);
\path [line] (student) -- node[anchor=west] {Reconstructs} (patterns);
\path [line] (student) -- node[anchor=north] {Minimizes} (examples);

\path [line] (data) -- node[anchor=west] {Provides} (labels);
\path [line] (data) -- node[anchor=north] {Defines} (patterns);
\path [line] (examples) -- node[anchor=west] {Trains} (labels);
\path [line] (examples) -- node[anchor=north] {Determines} (patterns);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

